{"numsheets":1,"currentid":"sheet1","currentname":"sheet4","sheetArr":{"sheet1":{"sheetstr":{"savestr":"version:1.5\ncell:B3:t:Introduction:f:2:c:3:bg:1:cf:1\ncell:B6:t:Diabetes Management application enables you to record your blood sugar levels. Two sheets have been provided, that highlight the symptoms of hypoglycemia as well as calculate your risk score for diabetes.  A Monthly Calendar, a Blood Sugar Tracker and Physical Activity Record sheet have been provided along with a weekly meal planner. A checklist has also been provided, that helps you to self-evaluate your outpatient management of diabetes.\ncell:B8:t:Blood Sugar Log sheet helps you record your blood sugar readings on a daily basis for two months. The log has been designed for taking the readings four times per day. Special notes about the reading can also be entered at your convenience. The record is also visualised with a graph.:bg:2\ncell:B10:t:The Monthly Calendar sheet provides a note taking feature to help you keep a track of your health on a daily basis for the entire month. Checkmark functionality has been provided, that lets you highlight the important dates easily.\ncell:B12:t:The Activity Log sheet lets you track and summarize the time spent on the physical activities on a weekly basis. The activities may range from walking, jogging, cycling, etc. to any other physical exercise that has been prescribed by your doctor. Goals can be set on a daily basis, and can be compared regularly using the log sheets.:bg:2\ncell:B14:t:The Meal Planner helps you to plan and organise your various meals in order to follow a certain diet plan.\ncell:B16:t:The Medical Guidelines checklist has been created on a set of performance measures that can be used to evaluate outpatient management of an adult patient with diabetes mellitus. This sheet has been intended as a self-check for the user.:bg:2\ncell:B18:t:The Symptoms sheet lists the clinical symptoms of hypoglycemia, and is intended as a self check to realise if immediate medical attention is needed. \ncell:B20:t:The Risk Score helps you in identifying your risk for developing diabetes. The scale is based on the Risk Score of Ramachandran et al for Diabetes in an Urban Asian Indian and helps in identifying the patients who will benefit from closer monitoring. It is included with the intent, to help you realise how serous the situation might be and whether further tests should be taken immediately.:bg:2\ncell:B22:t:Entering data is simple. Tap on the cell to edit and add the text. Locally save your Diabetes Risk app as a file, and re-use it with minimal changes. Simply tap e-mail to send it to your family or doctor instantly and get feedback from them. Alternatively, you can email it to yourself.\ncell:B24:t:If you need any further assistance in using the Diabetes Risk app, or would like to see some new features in the future versions of the application, please write to us at marketing@tickervalue.com You can also meet us on Skype by sending a contact request to aspiring.investments:bg:2\ncell:B26:t:Note\\cReferences\\nRamachandran A, Snehalatha C, et al. Derivation and validation of diabetes risk score for urban Asian Indians. Diabetes Research and Clinical Practice. 2005; 70\\c 63-70.\\n\\nAmerican Medical Association, Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations, and the National Committee for Quality Assurance. Coordinated Performance Measurement for the Management of Adult Diabetes. April 2001.\ncol:A:w:10\ncol:B:w:672\nsheet:c:2:r:26:font:1:layout:1\ncellformat:1:center\ncolor:1:rgb(119,136,221)\ncolor:2:rgb(230,230,250)\ncolor:3:rgb(255, 255, 255)\nfont:1:* 11pt arial,helvetica,sans-serif\nfont:2:* 18pt *\nlayout:1:padding:4px 2px 4px 2px;vertical-align:*;\n"},"name":"sheet4","hidden":"0"}}}